"Elephant cannot capture Rat. However, Rat can capture Elephant."

But elephant has more strength than rat hm? If this is the exception, it should be more clear.

- In rules is provided start position of any animal.
- Each turn is provided made turn of opponent.
- my color is provided in input.

So player is needed by ourself calculate, what opponent (and also own) animal is where.

wouldn't it be better to provide each turn a list (nrAnimals):
- owner (0 - opponent, 1 - me)
- animal (CAT, WOLF...)
- x/y position

That:
- makes my color input redundant
- enemy from / to move redundant (but would probably be still nice)

Nice game!

After some testing, everything looks good!

* According to the Wikipedia link, a Dog has strength 3 and a Wolf is 4. This affects the statement and the referee.
* The Game Summary uses algebraic notation but is completely broken.

It would be handy for novice players to have the game board representation in the inputs eg
l.#@#.t
.d.#.c.
r.p.w.e
.XX.XX.
.XX.XX.
.XX.XX.
E.W.P.R
.C.#.D.
T.#@#.L
for the starting position. Perhaps, den, traps and water position is too much
It would seem more familiar to me to issue moves in algebraic notation (eg A5 B5)

From original game rules: "A piece that enters one of the opponent's trap squares is reduced in rank to 0. Thus the trapped piece may be captured by the defending side with any piece, regardless of rank. A trapped piece has its normal rank restored when it exits an opponent's trap square."

Here it's a variant without rank restoration and with universal traps - any animal rank is reduced to 0?
Clarify it in the statement please.

Would be handy to have digit rank idicator on each piece, for better human understanding which animal is which and when rank goes to 0. Like here http://www.onlinesologames.com/animal-chess

I played the game on this site before and the rules there are weird I think.

Not sure what you mean by "rank restored". If you stay on the trap your strength is 0. I think it is hard to write it more clearly.

Traps are universal because the game has some drawish/perfect defense issues without.

About the indicator on a piece - good point - I will add them to tooltips and maybe on normal pieces also.
The game is not actually played on a chessboard,  and algebraic notation is always a little pain to deal with, so I skipped using it this time ^^'

I was considering this but rejected.
Having symbols for all animals in traps, rats on water etc is too inconvinient imo.

There are so many variants of this game, half place wolf above dog, half otherwise (without changing positions). To avoid confusion, I removed links as they contradict each other.

Thanks for summary finding - I was using some old function instead of proper one.
Thx for the bugs you've found so far :kissing_cat:.

Elephant cannot go in water :-D https://www.codingame.com/replay/766832586

The nice graphics helps me debug my moves though.

I thought the rat would help the lion but I guess I confused myself 😐

Not sure why I did 150ms, I suppose the reason was our python students trying hard to make any MCTS work.
But yeah, probably it would be better to reduce it.
int x = move[0] - 'A', y = move[1] - '1'; // solved ;-)

Currently, statement says: "Animal staying on a trap has its strength reduced to 0."
In my understanding, when a piece's rank/strength was reduced once, it remained at 0.  
Maybe you can rephrase it to: while a piece is staying on the trap, its strength is 0 temporally. Or use quote from first post.

I referred to Wikipedia as original rules. That online game was just as an example of  indicator on a piece they use
